<DOC><DOCNO> AP881205-0209 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0758EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv16   12-05 0494</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv 16,0513</SECOND><NOTE>$adv16</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Friday, Dec. 16</NOTE><HEAD>Today In History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Friday, Dec. 16, the 351st day of 1988. There are 15days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   In 1773, the Boston Tea Party took place as American colonists,disguised as Indians, boarded a British ship in Boston Harbor anddumped more than 300 chests of tea overboard in a protest againsttaxes.   On this date:   In 1653, Oliver Cromwell became lord protector of England,Scotland and Ireland.   In 1770, the German composer Ludwig van Beethoven was born inBonn, Germany.   In 1809, Napoleon Bonaparte was divorced from the EmpressJosephine by an act of the French Senate.   In 1905, the entertainment trade publication Variety came outwith its first weekly issue.   In 1916, Gregory Rasputin, the monk who wielded powerfulinfluence over the Russian court, was murdered.   In 1944, the World War II Battle of the Bulge began in Belgium.   In 1950, President Harry S. Truman proclaimed a national state ofemergency in order to fight ``Communist imperialism.''   In 1960, 134 people were killed when a United Air Lines DC-8 anda TWA Super Constellation collided over New York City and crashed.   In 1976, the government halted its swine flu vaccination programfollowing reports of paralysis apparently linked to the vaccine.   In 1981, police clashed with striking coal miners at the Wujekpit in Katowice in southern Poland. Nine miners were fatally injured.   In 1982, Environmental Protection Agency head Anne M. Gorsuch(later Burford) became the first Cabinet-level officer to be citedfor contempt of Congress for her refusal to submit documentsrequested by a congressional committee.   In 1985, at services in Fort Campbell, Ky., President and Mrs.Reagan offered condolences to the families of 248 soldiers killed inthe crash of a chartered plane in Newfoundland.   In 1985, reputed organized-crime chief Paul Castellano was shotto death outside a New York City restaurant.   Ten years ago: Former California Gov. Ronald Reagan joined otherconservatives in denouncing President Jimmy Carter's decision torecognize the People's Republic of China, calling it an ``outrightbetrayal of our close friend and ally,'' Taiwan.   Five years ago: A judge in Riverside, Calif., denied a requestfrom cerebral palsy victim Elizabeth Bouvia to starve herself todeath in a county hospital. (Bouvia, a paraplegic, had said she didnot want to live ``trapped in a useless body.'')   One year ago: Former deputy White House chief of staff Michael K.Deaver, a close associate of President and Mrs. Reagan, wasconvicted of lying under oath to a grand jury and a congressionalsubcommittee.   Today's birthdays: Author Victor S. Pritchett is 88. AuthorArthur C. Clarke is 71. Actress Liv Ullmann is 49. CBS Newscorrespondent Lesley Stahl is 47. Football player William ``TheRefrigerator'' Perry is 26.   Thought for today: ``Nations, like individuals, have to limittheir objectives or take the consequences.'' _ James Reston,American journalist.</TEXT></DOC>